						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">MetalSlime wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">UncleSporky wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">For organizing something like this, I've thought about a lookup table system.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">VideoRoutine:<br />.dw TitleVideo, GameVideo, StatusVideo<br /><br />ControlRoutine:<br />.dw TitleControl, GameControl, StatusControl</div></div><br /><br />To clarify, would these data words hold the addresses where the routines are located, i.e. the addresses you want to jump to?</div><br />Yes, those are just labels that get processed as addresses by the assembler.  You use them as normal before the routines:<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">TitleVideo:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;blah blah<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;rts<br /><br />GameControl:<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;blah blah<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;rts</div>
<br />
<br />Again, I don't know if that's a good way to do it but it feels nicely organized.</div>

